# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: article-of-commerce
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] In the 21st-century there has been a revival of serious interest in communism, led by Slavoj Žižek and Alain Badiou.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] This interest was propelled by the 2008 financial crisis which saw many books published offering communist and Marxist analyses of the crisis, and the 2009 conference "The Idea of Communism", that brought together many of theorists.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] The interest in 21st-century theorists writing about communism spans a broad range of communist traditions.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] According to the political theorist Alan Johnson, there has been a revival of serious interest in communism in the 21st century led by Slavoj Žižek and Alain Badiou.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] In 2009, many advocates for and theorists of communism in the 21st century contributed to the three-day conference, "The Idea of Communism", in London that drew a substantial paying audience.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Journals such as *Endnotes*, *Salvage, Ebb Magazine* *Kites* and *Historical Materialism* launched with communist outlooks, as well as news outlets such as Novara Media.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Furthermore, internet culture and declining life prospects has led to a general rise amongst Millennials and Gen-Z in support for communism and socialism, in tandem with the rise of left-populism in the US and the UK.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Explicitly left-wing contemporary artists, such as filmmakers, musicians, video-game creators and comedians have received widespread attention, such as the rapper/producer JPEGMafia, and a whole media-creator ecosystem has developed around the online left, known as BreadTube.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Other non-Marxist thinkers who have also had an effect on the 'new communists' include the revolutionaries Subcomandante Marcos and Abdullah Öcalan, abolitionist Ruth Wilson Gilmore, economist Frédéric Lordon, architecture journalist Owen Hatherley, and the late anthropologist David Graeber.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] According to Slavoj Žižek, the book *Empire* by the autonomists Michael Hardt and Antonio Negri, was a major turning stone in 21st-century Marxist and communist thought.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Theoretical publications, some published by Verso Books, include *The Idea of Communism*, edited by Costas Douzinas and Žižek; Badiou's *The Communist Hypothesis*; and Bosteels's *The Actuality of Communism*.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Communism as a radical philosophical idea.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] It must be thought of as taking distance from economism and statism as well as learning from the experiences of the 21st century.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Communism combats neoliberalism by returning to the idea of the "common".
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Equality cannot exist without freedom and vice versa.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] A rise in Marxist thought followed the 2008 financial crisis, with the publishing of books including G.
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] Cohen's *Why Not Socialism?* (2009), Paul Paolucci's *Marx's Scientific Dialectics* (2009), Kieran Allen's *Marx and the Alternative to Capitalism* (2011), Terry Eagleton's *Why Marx Was Right* (2011) and Vincent Mosco's *Marx Is Back* (2012).
[src:article-of-commerce/21st-century-communist-theorists] *The Communist Horizon*, published in 2012 by Jodi Dean, marked the beginning in a series of books from Dean which argue for the necessity of communist and Leninist politics.
[src:article-of-commerce/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Much of the *Critique* was later incorporated by Marx into his *magnum opus*, *Capital* (Volume I), published in 1867, and the *Critique* is generally considered to be of secondary importance among Marx's writings.
[src:article-of-commerce/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] This does not apply, however, to the Preface of the *Critique*.
[src:article-of-commerce/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Marx expressed this himself in the preface of the book: "It is not the consciousness of men that determines their being, but, on the contrary, their social being that determines (German: *bestimmt*, lit.
[src:article-of-commerce/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] In English, *A Contribution to the Critique of Political Economy* is available in an edition edited by Maurice Dobb, published by Progress Publishers, Moscow (translation by S.
[src:article-of-commerce/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Lawrence and Wishart (London), and International Publishers (New York) cooperated in the publication of the Progress Publishers edition.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] So, Marx argues that human work is both (1) an activity which, by its useful effect, helps to create particular kinds of products, and (2) in an economic sense, a *value-forming* activity that, if it is productively applied, can help create more value than there was before.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If an employer hires labour, the employer thinks both about how useful the labour service will be for his business operations, and about the value that the labour can create for his business.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is, the right kind of work not only needs to get done, but it also needs to get done in a way that it helps the employer to make money.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If the labour makes no net addition to new value produced, then the employer makes no money from it.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The labour will be only an expense to him.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If the labour is only a net expense (overhead), then it is commercially speaking *unproductive* labour.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Yet, it may be very necessary to employ this unproductive labour.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If that labour was not done, then considerable capital value might be *lost* from the employer's financial investments.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Indeed, the business might fail without it.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is, labour may be very necessary to *maintain* capital value, although it does not actually *add* value to capital, and does not directly add to net profit.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] So, the employer also buys the "unproductive labour", because it reduces his costs.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] His labour costs will be lower than the *loss* of value that would occur, if he did not employ unproductive labour to *maintain* capital value, and to prevent loss of capital value.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] For example, cleaning work might seem a very menial and low-value activity.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] But if business equipment fails, customers stay away, and the staff get sick or injured, it costs the business a lot of extra money.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the *Grundrisse*, Marx also distinguished between "particular labour" and "general labour", contrasting communal production with production for exchange.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx himself considered that all economising reduced to the economical use of human labour-time; "to economise" ultimately meant saving on human energy and effort.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However, according to Marx, the achievement of abstract thinking about human labour, and the ability to quantify it, is closely related to the historical development of economic exchange in general, and more specifically commodity trade (the trade in wares and merchandise).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The expansion of trade requires the ability to measure and compare all kinds of things - not just length, volume and weight, but also time itself.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Originally, the units of measurement used were taken from everyday life—the length of a finger or limb, the volume of an ordinary container, the weight one can carry, the duration of a day or a season, the number of cattle.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In a biblical story where God delivers moral guidelines to Moses which people must follow, dishonest measures and mismeasurement are explicitly prohibited: “You shall do no wrong in judgment, in measures of length or weight or quantity.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] You shall have just balances, just weights…" (Leviticus 19:35).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Once standard measuring units existed, mathematics could begin to develop.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In fact, Marx argues the abstraction of labour in thought is *the reflex of a real process*, in which commercial trade in products not only alters the way labour is *viewed*, but also how it is practically *treated*.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In other words, when labour becomes a commercial object traded in the marketplace, then the form and content of work in the workplace is transformed as well, to conform to commercial requirements.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This transformation is practically possible, because labour already contains the potential to adapt to the requirements of capitalist business.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This potential has already been shaped up by previous schooling and training.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Therefore, Marx implies, the exchange process itself *involves the making of a real abstraction*, namely abstraction from (or indifference to) the particular characteristics of concrete (specific) labour that produced the commodities whose value is equated in trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] At first, the relationship between quantities of traded commodities symbolically represents relative costs in labour time.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This relationship is ordinarily quite transparent because goods are traded by the people who produced them.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Next, money-prices begin to represent symbolically the commodities being traded.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In this way, a system of symbolic representation emerges which can facilitate the exchange of the most diverse products with great efficiency.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the end, products as commodities become simply objects of value, and since their value can rise and fall, they can be bought and sold purely for capital gain.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In a more complex division of labour, it becomes difficult or even impossible to equate the value of all different labour-efforts directly.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] But money enables us to express and compare the value of *all* different labour-efforts—more or less accurately—in money-units (initially, quantities of gold, silver, or bronze).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx then argues that labour viewed concretely in its specifics creates useful things, but labour-in-the-abstract is value-forming labour, which conserves, transfers and/or creates economic value (see Valorisation).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Quite simply, in this case, a quantity of labour-time is equal to a quantity of money, and it can be calculated that X hours of labour—regardless of who in particular performs them—create, or are worth, Y amounts of new product value.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In this way, labour is *practically* rendered abstract.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This is what Marx calls a *value relationship* ("Wertverhältnis" in German).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] It can also be calculated that it costs a certain amount of time and money to train a worker to perform a certain task, and how much value that adds to the workers' labour, giving rise to the notion of human capital.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] As a corollary, in these conditions workers will increasingly treat the paid work they do as something distinct or separate from their personality, a means to an end rather than an end in itself.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Work becomes "just work", it no longer *necessarily* says anything at all about the identity, creativity or personality of the worker.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] With the development of an average skill level in the workforce, the same job can also be done by many different workers, and most workers can do many different jobs; nobody is necessarily tied to one type of work all his life anymore.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Thus we can talk of "a job" as an abstract function that could be filled by anybody with the required skills.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Managers can calculate that with a certain budget, a certain number of paid working hours are required or available to do the work, and then divide up the hours into different job functions to be filled by suitably qualified personnel.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx's theory of alienation considers the human and social implications of the abstraction and commercialization of labour.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] His concept of reification reflects about the inversions of object and subject, and of means and ends, which are involved in commodity trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx regarded the distinction between abstract and concrete labour as being among the most important innovations he contributed to the theory of economic value, and subsequently Marxian scholars have debated a great deal about its theoretical significance.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] For ultraleftist Marxists, abstract labour is an economic category which applies only to the capitalist mode of production, i.e. it applies only, when human labour power or work-capacity is universally treated as a commodity with a certain monetary cost or earnings potential.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The logical implication of this ultraleftist interpretation is, that if capitalism is destroyed (by the revolutionary Marxist Party and the working class), then abstract labour is also destroyed and eradicated.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Other Marx-scholars, such as Makoto Itoh, take a more evolutionary view (like Marx did and archaeologists do).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Originally, in ancient society and medieval society ("premodern" or "pre-bourgeois" society), commodity production *co-existed* with subsistence production, a situation of "*partial* commodity production" (see also simple commodity production).
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Such a division of labour featuring partial commodity production is already achieved in many different *precapitalist societies*, and consequently the category of abstract labour already existed in precapitalist societies.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The category of abstract labour is fully realized because it becomes an objectified quantity.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Another controversy concerns the differences between unskilled (simple) and skilled (qualified) labour.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Skilled labour costs more to produce than unskilled labour, and can be more productive.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This was reflected in a skill hierarchy, and a hierarchy of wage-levels.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx believed that the capitalist mode of production would over time replace people with machines, and encourage the easy replacement of one worker by another, and thus that most labour would tend to reduce to an average skill level and standardized norms of work effort.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However he provided no specific calculus by which the value of skilled work could be expressed as a multiple of unskilled work, nor a theory of what regulates the valuation of skill differences.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This has led to some theoretical debate among Marxian economists, but no definitive solution has yet been given.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the first volume of *Das Kapital* Marx had declared his intention to write a special study of the forms of labour-compensation, but he never did so.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In contemporary society, a division is emerging between creative, skilled and specialized jobs attracting extraordinarily large salaries, and routine jobs paying very low salaries, where the enormous differences in pay rates are difficult to explain.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The economist Anwar Shaikh from the New School for Social Research has analyzed input-output data, wage data and labour data for the US economy, to create an *empirically testable* economic theory of the market valuation of skill differences.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The counterargument is, that the valuation of skills in a heavily bureaucratized education system depends to a great extent on the *balance of class forces* between the rich educated class, and the "lower-skilled" working class.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The rent-seeking educated class, on this view, can often raise its income far beyond the real worth of its work, if they occupy a privileged position, if its specialist skills happen to be in short supply or in demand, or if they are hired through the "old boy" networks.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is to say, to an extent, the assumed skill level of the employee may be more imaginary, than real; it all depends on how skills, experience and qualifications are defined and valued by privileged professionals whose rules reward their own kind the most.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Skilled labour may be over-valued and unskilled labour under-valued at the same time.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx did not think there was anything particularly mysterious about the fact that people valued products because they have to spend time working to produce them, or to buy them.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However, academics have made many objections to his idea.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The conceptual issues associated with the idea of abstract labour have been one of the main reasons why many economists abandoned the labour theory of value.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] It may be that the problems have never been resolved because they have been approached far too abstractly, using conceptual distinctions not really adequate for the purpose.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Replying to this type of criticism, the Russian Marxist Isaak Illich Rubin argued that the concept of abstract labour was really much more complex than it seemed at first sight.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] He distinguished between "physically equal" labour, labour which is "socially equated" by means of consensual social evaluation or comparison, and labour efforts equated via the exchange of products using money as a universal equivalent.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Some further aspects of the concept of abstract labour are provided by Marxian anthropologist Lawrence Krader and the mathematician Ulrich Krause.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Possibly, these conceptual issues can be resolved, through a better empirical appreciation of the political economy of education, skills and the labour market.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In his book *Crack Capitalism*, John Holloway considers abstract labour as the most radical foundational category of Marx's theory, and therefore he recommends the struggle against abstract labour as the centrepiece of the political struggle against capitalism.
[src:article-of-commerce/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The British computer scientist Paul Cockshott in 2013 wrote a piece critical of the German Marxist academic Michael Heinrich who, Cockshott argued, wrongly reinterpreted the concept of abstract labour so that it is no longer a scientifically testable concept.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Born in Kirkcaldy, Fife, he studied social philosophy at the University of Glasgow and at the University of Oxford, where he was one of the only students to benefit from scholarships set up by John Snell.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Following his graduation, he delivered a successful series of public lectures at the University of Edinburgh, that met with acclaim.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] This led to a collaboration with David Hume during the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith obtained a professorship at Glasgow, where he taught moral philosophy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] During this period, he wrote and published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Subsequently, he assumed a tutoring position that facilitated travel throughout Europe, where he encountered intellectual figures of his era.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In response to the prevailing policy of safeguarding national markets and merchants through the reduction of imports and the augmentation of exports, a practice that came to be known as mercantilism, Smith laid the foundational principles of classical free-market economic theory.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was a precursor to the modern academic discipline of economics.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In this and other works, he developed the concept of division of labour and expounded upon how rational self-interest and competition can lead to economic prosperity.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith was controversial in his day and his general approach and writing style were often satirised by writers such as Horace Walpole.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Adam Smith was born in Kirkcaldy, in Fife, Scotland.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] His father, Adam Smith senior, was a Scottish Writer to the Signet (senior solicitor), advocate and prosecutor (judge advocate) and also served as comptroller of the customs in Kirkcaldy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's mother was born Margaret Douglas, daughter of the landed Robert Douglas of Strathendry, also in Fife; she married Smith's father in 1720.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Two months before Smith was born, his father died, leaving his mother a widow.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The date of Smith's baptism into the Church of Scotland at Kirkcaldy was 5 June 1723 and this has often been treated as if it were also his date of birth, which is unknown.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Although few events in Smith's early childhood are known, the Scottish journalist John Rae, a biographer of Smith, recorded that Smith was abducted by Romani at the age of three and released when others went to rescue him.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith was close to his mother, who probably encouraged him to pursue his scholarly ambitions.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith entered the University of Glasgow at age 14 and studied moral philosophy under Francis Hutcheson.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Here he developed his passion for the philosophical concepts of reason, civilian liberties and the freedom of speech.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1740 he was the graduate scholar presented to undertake postgraduate studies at the Balliol College of the University of Oxford, under the Snell Exhibition.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith considered the teaching at Glasgow to be far superior to that at Oxford, which he found intellectually stifling.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to William Robert Scott, "The Oxford of [Smith's] time gave little if any help towards what was to be his lifework." Nevertheless, he took the opportunity while at Oxford to teach himself several subjects by reading many books from the shelves of the large Bodleian Library.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] When Smith was not studying on his own, his time at Oxford was not a happy one, according to his letters.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Near the end of his time there, he began suffering from shaking fits, probably the symptoms of a nervous breakdown.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He left Oxford in 1746, before his scholarship ended.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's curriculum at Glasgow included logic, metaphysics, moral philosophy, and natural philosophy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Under Hutcheson, Smith debated questions of natural justice, fair exchange, and the moral dimensions of commerce; themes which would be reflected in *The Wealth of Nations*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Hutcheson argued that workers deserved compensation sufficient to sustain themselves and their families, a concept Smith would later develop into his broader theory of natural wage levels.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In Book V of *The Wealth of Nations*, Smith comments on the low quality of instruction and the meager intellectual activity at English universities, when compared to their Scottish counterparts.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith began delivering public lectures in 1748 at the University of Edinburgh, sponsored by the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh under the patronage of Lord Kames.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] His lecture topics included rhetoric and *belles-lettres*, and later the subject of "the progress of opulence".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] On this latter topic, he first expounded his economic philosophy of "the obvious and simple system of natural liberty".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] While Smith was not adept at public speaking, his lectures met with success.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1750 Smith met the philosopher David Hume, who was his senior by more than a decade.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In their writings covering history, politics, philosophy, economics, and religion, Smith and Hume shared closer intellectual and personal bonds than with other important figures of the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1751 Smith earned a professorship at Glasgow teaching logic courses, and in 1752, he was elected a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh, having been introduced to the society by Henry Home, Lord Kames.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The following year, when the position of head of Moral Philosophy in Glasgow became vacant, Smith took over the role.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He worked as an academic for the next 13 years, which he characterised as "by far the most useful and therefore by far the happiest and most honorable period [of his life]".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith published *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* in 1759, embodying some of his Glasgow lectures.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] This work was concerned with how human morality depends on sympathy between agent and spectator, or the individual and other members of society.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith defined "mutual sympathy" as the basis of moral sentiments.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Following the publication of *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith became so popular that many wealthy students left their schools in other countries to enroll at Glasgow to learn under Smith.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] At this time, Smith began to give more attention to jurisprudence and economics in his lectures and less to his theories of morals.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] For example, Smith lectured that the cause of increase in national wealth is labour, rather than the nation's quantity of gold or silver, which is the basis for mercantilism, the economic theory that dominated Western European economic policies at the time.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1762, the University of Glasgow conferred on Smith the title of Doctor of Laws (LL.D.).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] At the end of 1763, he obtained an offer from the chancellor of the exchequer, Charles Townshend—who had been introduced to Smith by David Hume—to tutor his stepson, Henry Scott, the young Duke of Buccleuch as preparation for a career in international politics.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith resigned from his professorship in 1764 to take the tutoring position.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He subsequently attempted to return the fees he had collected from his students because he had resigned partway through the term, but his students refused.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's tutoring job entailed touring Europe with Scott, during which time he educated Scott on a variety of subjects.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He was paid £300 per year (plus expenses) along with a £300-per-year pension; roughly twice his former income as a teacher.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith first travelled as a tutor to Toulouse, France, where he stayed for a year and a half.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to his own account, he found Toulouse to be somewhat boring, having written to Hume that he "had begun to write a book to pass away the time".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] After touring the south of France the group moved to Geneva, where Smith met the French writer and philosopher Voltaire.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In Paris Smith encountered the Physiocracy school founded by François Quesnay and conversed with their intellectuals.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Physiocrats were opposed to mercantilism, the dominating economic theory of the time, illustrated in their motto *Laissez faire et laissez passer, le monde va de lui même!* (Let do and let pass, the world goes on by itself!).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The wealth of France had been virtually depleted by Louis XIV and Louis XV in ruinous wars, and was further exhausted in aiding the American revolutionary soldiers, against the British.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1766 Henry Scott's younger brother died in Paris, and Smith's tour as a tutor ended shortly thereafter.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith returned home that year to Kirkcaldy, and he devoted much of the next decade to writing his *magnum opus*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] There, he befriended Henry Moyes, a young blind man who showed precocious aptitude.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith secured the patronage of David Hume and Thomas Reid in the young man's education.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In May 1767 Smith was elected fellow of the Royal Society of London, and was elected a member of the Literary Club in 1775.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] *The Wealth of Nations* was published in 1776 and was an instant success, selling out its first edition in only six months.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1778 Smith was appointed to a post as commissioner of customs in Scotland and went to live with his mother (who died in 1784) in Panmure House in the Canongate in Edinburgh.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Five years later, as a member of the Philosophical Society of Edinburgh when it received its royal charter, he automatically became one of the founding members of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] From 1787 to 1789 he occupied the honorary position of Lord Rector of the University of Glasgow.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith died in the northern wing of Panmure House in Edinburgh on 17 July 1790 after a painful illness.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] His body was buried in the Canongate Kirkyard.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] On his deathbed, Smith expressed disappointment that he had not achieved more.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's literary executors were two friends from the Scottish academic world: the physicist and chemist Joseph Black and the pioneering geologist James Hutton.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith left behind many notes and some unpublished material, but gave instructions to destroy anything that was not fit for publication.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He mentioned an early unpublished *History of Astronomy* as probably suitable, and it duly appeared in 1795, along with other material such as *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's library went by his will to David Douglas, Lord Reston (son of his cousin Colonel Robert Douglas of Strathendry, Fife), who lived with Smith.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] It was eventually divided between Douglas's two surviving children, Cecilia Margaret (Mrs.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] On the death in 1878 of her husband, the Reverend W.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The remainder passed to her son, Professor Robert Oliver Cunningham of Queen's College, Belfast, who presented a part to the library of Queen's College.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] After his death, the remaining books were sold.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Bannerman in 1879, her portion of the library went intact to the New College (of the Free Church) in Edinburgh and the collection was transferred to the University of Edinburgh Main Library in 1972.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Not much is known about Smith's personal views beyond what can be deduced from his published articles.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] His personal papers were destroyed after his death, per his request.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He never married, and seems to have maintained a close relationship with his mother, with whom he lived after his return from France and who died six years before him.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith was described by several of his contemporaries and biographers as comically absent-minded, with peculiar habits of speech and gait, and a smile of "inexpressible benignity".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He was known to talk to himself, a habit that began during his childhood when he would smile in rapt conversation with invisible companions.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He also had occasional spells of imaginary illness, and he is reported to have had books and papers placed in tall stacks in his study.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to one story, Smith took Charles Townshend on a tour of a tanning factory, and while discussing free trade, Smith walked into a huge tanning pit from which he needed help to escape.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He is also said to have put bread and butter into a teapot, drunk the concoction, and declared it to be the worst cup of tea he had ever had.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to another account, Smith distractedly went out walking in his nightgown and ended up 15 miles (24 km) outside town, before nearby church bells brought him back to reality.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] James Boswell, who was a student of Smith's at Glasgow University, and later knew him at the Literary Club, says that Smith thought that speaking about his ideas in conversation might reduce the sale of his books, so his conversation was unimpressive.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to Boswell, he once told Sir Joshua Reynolds, that "he made it a rule when in company never to talk of what he understood".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith has been alternatively described as someone who "had a large nose, bulging eyes, a protruding lower lip, a nervous twitch, and a speech impediment" and one whose "countenance was manly and agreeable".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith is said to have acknowledged his looks at one point, saying, "I am a beau in nothing but my books." Smith rarely sat for portraits, so almost all depictions of him created during his lifetime were drawn from memory.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The best-known portraits of Smith are the profile by James Tassie and two etchings by John Kay.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The line engravings produced for the covers of 19th-century reprints of *The Wealth of Nations* were based largely on Tassie's medallion.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Considerable scholarly debate has occurred about the nature of Smith's religious views.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] His father had shown a strong interest in Christianity and belonged to the moderate wing of the Church of Scotland, and the fact that he received the Snell Exhibition suggests that he may have gone to Oxford with the intention of pursuing a career in the Church of England.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The British economist Ronald Coase challenged the view that Smith was a deist, based on the fact that Smith's writings never explicitly invoke God as an explanation of the harmonies of the natural or the human worlds.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Philosophy afterwards endeavoured to account for them, from more familiar causes, or from such as mankind were better acquainted with than the agency of the gods".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Some authors argue that Smith's social and economic philosophy is inherently theological and that his entire model of social order is logically dependent on the notion of God's action in nature.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Brendan Long argues that Smith was a theist, whereas according to Gavin Kennedy, Smith was "in some sense" a Christian.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith was also a close friend of David Hume, who, despite debate about his religious views in modern scholarship, was commonly characterised in his own time as an atheist.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The publication in 1777 of Smith's letter to William Strahan, in which he described Hume's courage in the face of death in spite of his irreligiosity, attracted considerable controversy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In 1759 Smith published his first work, *The Theory of Moral Sentiments,* sold by the co-publishers Andrew Millar of London and Alexander Kincaid of Edinburgh.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith continued making extensive revisions to the book until his death.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Although *The Wealth of Nations* is widely regarded as Smith's most influential work, Smith himself is believed to have considered *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* to be a superior work.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith proposes a theory of sympathy, in which the act of observing others and seeing the judgements they form of both others and oneself makes people aware of themselves and how others perceive their behaviour.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The feedback received by an individual from perceiving (or imagining) others' judgement creates an incentive to achieve "mutual sympathy of sentiments" with them and leads people to develop habits, and then principles, of behaviour, which come to constitute one's conscience.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] While scholars have historically recognised a conflict - often phrased the "Adam Smith Problem"-between the exaggeration on sympathy in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and self-interest in *The Wealth of Nations*, modern scholarship largely overlooks this contradiction.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Instead the two works are widely seen as part of a unified system of moral and economic philosophy that are able to co-exist and complement each other.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] These scholars contend that in *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, Smith develops a theory of psychology in which individuals seek the approval of the "impartial spectator" as a result of a natural desire to have outside observers sympathise with their sentiments.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Rather than viewing *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and *The Wealth of Nations* as presenting incompatible views of human nature, some Smith scholars regard the works as emphasising different aspects of human nature that vary depending on the situation.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In the first part – *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* – he laid down the foundation of his vision of humanity and society.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In the second – *The Wealth of Nations* – he elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] It was his plan to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] James Otteson argues that both books are Newtonian in their methodology and deploy a similar "market model" for explaining the creation and development of large-scale human social orders, including morality, economics, as well as language.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Disagreement exists between classical and neoclassical economists about the central message of Smith's most influential work: *An Inquiry into the Nature and Causes of the Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He elaborated on the virtue of prudence, which for him meant the relations between people in the private sphere of the economy.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] He planned to further elaborate on the virtue of justice in the third book.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith used the term "the invisible hand" in "History of Astronomy" referring to "the invisible hand of Jupiter", and once in each of his *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* (1759) and *The Wealth of Nations* (1776).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] This last statement about "an invisible hand" has been interpreted in numerous ways.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In relation to Bernard Mandeville's contention that "Private Vices ... may be turned into Public Benefits", Smith's belief that when an individual pursues his self-interest under conditions of justice, he unintentionally promotes the good of society.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Self-interested competition in the free market, he argued, would tend to benefit society as a whole by keeping prices low, while still building in an incentive for a wide variety of goods and services.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith states that the interest of manufacturers and merchants "in any particular branch of trade or manufactures, is always in some respects different from, and even opposite to, that of the public ...
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The neoclassical interest in Smith's statement about "an invisible hand" originates in the possibility of seeing it as a precursor of neoclassical economics and its concept of general equilibrium; Paul Samuelson's "Economics" refers six times to Smith's "invisible hand".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] To emphasise this connection, Samuelson quotes Smith's "invisible hand" statement substituting "general interest" for "public interest".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Samuelson concludes: "Smith was unable to prove the essence of his invisible-hand doctrine.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Conversely, classical economists see in Smith's first sentences his programme to promote "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Using the physiocratical concept of the economy as a circular process, to secure growth the inputs of Period 2 must exceed the inputs of Period 1.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Therefore, those outputs of Period 1 which are not used or usable as inputs of Period 2 are regarded as unproductive labour, as they do not contribute to growth.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] This is what Smith had heard in France from, among others, François Quesnay, whose ideas Smith was so impressed by that he might have dedicated *The Wealth of Nations* to him had he not died beforehand.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] To this French insight that unproductive labour should be reduced to use labour more productively, Smith added his own proposal, that productive labour should be made even more productive by deepening the division of labour.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith argued that deepening the division of labour under competition leads to greater productivity, which leads to lower prices and thus an increasing standard of living—"general plenty" and "universal opulence"—for all.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Extended markets and increased production lead to the continuous reorganisation of production and the invention of new ways of producing, which in turn lead to further increased production, lower prices, and improved standards of living.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's central message is, therefore, that under dynamic competition, a growth machine secures "The Wealth of Nations".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith's argument predicted Britain's evolution as the workshop of the world, underselling and outproducing all its competitors.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] According to Smith, "It is not very unreasonable that the rich should contribute to the public expense, not only in proportion to their revenue, but something more in that proportion".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Smith wrote that a government is duty-bound to provide public services that "support the whole of society" like provide public education, transportation, national defence, a justice system, public safety, and public infrastructure to support commerce.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Shortly before his death, Smith had nearly all his manuscripts destroyed.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] In his last years, he seemed to have been planning two major treatises, one on the theory and history of law and one on the sciences and arts.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] The posthumously published *Essays on Philosophical Subjects*, a history of astronomy down to Smith's own era, plus some thoughts on ancient physics and metaphysics, probably contain parts of what would have been the latter treatise.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] *Lectures on Jurisprudence* were notes taken from Smith's early lectures, plus an early draft of *The Wealth of Nations*, published as part of the 1976 Glasgow Edition of the works and correspondence of Smith.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p01] Other works, including some published posthumously, include *Lectures on Justice, Police, Revenue, and Arms* (1763) (first published in 1896); and *Essays on Philosophical Subjects* (1795).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] In light of the arguments put forward by Smith and other economic theorists in Britain, academic belief in mercantilism began to decline in Britain in the late 18th century.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] During the Industrial Revolution, Britain embraced free trade and Smith's *laissez-faire* economics, and via the British Empire, used its power to spread a broadly liberal economic model around the world, characterised by open markets, and relatively barrier-free domestic and international trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] George Stigler attributes to Smith "the most important substantive proposition in all of economics".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] It is that, under competition, owners of resources (for example labour, land, and capital) will use them most profitably, resulting in an equal rate of return in equilibrium for all uses, adjusted for apparent differences arising from such factors as training, trust, hardship, and unemployment.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Paul Samuelson finds in Smith's pluralist use of supply and demand as applied to wages, rents, and profit a valid and valuable anticipation of the general equilibrium modelling of Léon Walras a century later.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith's allowance for wage increases in the short and intermediate term from capital accumulation and invention contrasted with Thomas Robert Malthus, David Ricardo, and Karl Marx in their propounding a rigid subsistence–wage theory of labour supply.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Joseph Schumpeter criticised Smith for a lack of technical rigour, yet he argued that this enabled Smith's writings to appeal to wider audiences: "His very limitation made for success.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Had he been more brilliant, he would not have been taken so seriously.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Had he dug more deeply, had he unearthed more recondite truth, had he used more difficult and ingenious methods, he would not have been understood.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] But he had no such ambitions; in fact he disliked whatever went beyond plain common sense.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He never moved above the heads of even the dullest readers.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Classical economists presented competing theories to those of Smith, termed the "labour theory of value".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Later Marxian economics descending from classical economics also use Smith's labour theories, in part.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The first volume of Marx's major work, *Das Kapital*, was published in German in 1867.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] In it Marx focused on the labour theory of value and what he considered to be the exploitation of labour by capital.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The labour theory of value held that the value of a thing was determined by the labour that went into its production.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] This contrasts with the modern contention of neoclassical economics, that the value of a thing is determined by what one is willing to give up to obtain the thing.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Frédéric Bastiat advocated a similar theory, that the value of a thing or service was its utility, or usefulness, to others.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] One example he used was of one finding a large diamond after having done little labor; yet it was still valuable because others wanted it.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The body of theory later termed "neoclassical economics" or "marginalism" formed from about 1870 to 1910.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The term "economics" was popularised by such neoclassical economists as Alfred Marshall as a concise synonym for "economic science" and a substitute for the earlier, broader term "political economy" used by Smith.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] This corresponded to the influence on the subject of mathematical methods used in the natural sciences.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Neoclassical economics systematised supply and demand as joint determinants of price and quantity in market equilibrium, affecting both the allocation of output and the distribution of income.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] It dispensed with the labour theory of value of which Smith was most famously identified with in classical economics, in favour of a marginal utility theory of value on the demand side and a more general theory of costs on the supply side.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The bicentennial anniversary of the publication of *The Wealth of Nations* was celebrated in 1976, resulting in increased interest for *The Theory of Moral Sentiments* and his other works throughout academia.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] After 1976 Smith was more likely to be represented as the author of both *The Wealth of Nations* and *The Theory of Moral Sentiments*, and thereby as the founder of a moral philosophy and the science of economics.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] His *homo economicus* or "economic man" was also more often represented as a moral person.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, economists David Levy and Sandra Peart in "The Secret History of the Dismal Science" point to his opposition to hierarchy and beliefs in equality, including racial equality, and provide additional support for those who point to Smith's opposition to slavery, colonialism, and empire.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Emphasised also are Smith's statements of the need for high wages for the poor, and the efforts to keep wages low.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] They also cite Smith's opposition to the often expressed view that science is superior to common sense.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He challenged ideas that colonies were key to British prosperity and power.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He rejected that other cultures, such as China and India, were culturally and developmentally inferior to Europe.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] While he favoured "commercial society", he did not support radical social change and the imposition of commercial society on other societies.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He proposed that colonies be given independence or that full political rights be extended to colonial subjects.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith's chapter on colonies, in turn, would help shape British imperial debates from the mid-19th century onward.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] *The Wealth of Nations* would become an ambiguous text regarding the imperial question.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] In his chapter on colonies, Smith pondered how to solve the crisis developing across the Atlantic among the empire's 13 American colonies.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He offered two different proposals for easing tensions.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The first proposal called for giving the colonies their independence, and by thus parting on a friendly basis, Britain would be able to develop and maintain a free-trade relationship with them, and possibly even an informal military alliance.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith's second proposal called for a theoretical imperial federation that would bring the colonies and the metropole closer together through an imperial parliamentary system and imperial free trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith's most prominent disciple in 19th-century Britain, the peace-advocate Richard Cobden, preferred the first proposal.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Cobden would lead the Anti-Corn Law League in overturning the Corn Laws in 1846, shifting Britain to a policy of free trade and empire "on the cheap" for decades to come.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] This hands-off approach toward the British Empire would become known as Cobdenism or the Manchester School.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] By the turn of the century, however, advocates of Smith's second proposal such as Joseph Shield Nicholson would become ever more vocal in opposing Cobdenism, calling instead for imperial federation.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] As Marc-William Palen notes: "On the one hand, Adam Smith's late nineteenth and early twentieth-century Cobdenite adherents used his theories to argue for gradual imperial devolution and empire 'on the cheap'.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Between 1867 and 1870, a statue of Smith was built into the outside wall of 6 Burlington Gardens, then the headquarters of the University of London (now home to the Royal Academy of Arts).
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] A large-scale memorial of Smith by Alexander Stoddart was unveiled on 4 July 2008 in Edinburgh.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] It is a 10-foot (3.0 m)-tall bronze sculpture and it stands above the Royal Mile outside St Giles' Cathedral in Parliament Square, near the Mercat cross.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Sculptor Jim Sanborn has created multiple pieces which feature Smith's work.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] At Central Connecticut State University is *Circulating Capital*, a tall cylinder which features an extract from *The Wealth of Nations* on the lower half, and on the upper half, some of the same text, but represented in binary code.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] At the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, outside the Belk College of Business Administration, is *Adam Smith's Spinning Top*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Another Smith sculpture is at Cleveland State University.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] A bust of Smith is in the Hall of Heroes of the National Wallace Monument in Stirling.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Five paving stones, displaying quotations from Smith's works, were unveiled in December 2023 on High Street in Glasgow.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] They were commissioned by the University of Glasgow to mark the 300th anniversary of Smith's birth.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Adam Smith resided at Panmure House from 1778 to 1790.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] In 2008, the house was purchased by the Edinburgh Business School at Heriot-Watt University and funds were raised for its restoration.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] In 2018 it was formally opened as a study centre in Smith's honour.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Other writers have argued that Smith's support for *laissez-faire* (which in French means leave alone) has been overstated.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Herbert Stein wrote that the people who "wear an Adam Smith necktie" do it to "make a statement of their devotion to the idea of free markets and limited government", and that this misrepresents Smith's ideas.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Stein writes that Smith "was not pure or doctrinaire about this idea.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He viewed government intervention in the market with great skepticism...yet he was prepared to accept or propose qualifications to that policy in the specific cases where he judged that their net effect would be beneficial and would not undermine the basically free character of the system.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He did not wear the Adam Smith necktie." In Stein's reading, *The Wealth of Nations* could justify the Food and Drug Administration, the Consumer Product Safety Commission, mandatory employer health benefits, environmentalism, and "discriminatory taxation to deter improper or luxurious behavior".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Some commentators have argued that Smith's works show support for a progressive, not flat, income tax and that he specifically named taxes that he thought should be required by the state, among them luxury-goods taxes and tax on rent.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Yet Smith argued for the "impossibility of taxing the people, in proportion to their economic revenue, by any capitation".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith argued that taxes should principally go toward protecting "justice" and "certain publick institutions" that were necessary for the benefit of all of society, which could not be adequately provided by private enterprise.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Additionally, Smith outlined the proper expenses of the government in *The Wealth of Nations, Book V, Ch.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Included in his requirements of a government is to enforce contracts and provide justice system, grant patents and copy rights, provide public goods such as infrastructure, provide national defence, and regulate banking.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The role of the government was to provide goods "of such a nature that the profit could never repay the expense to any individual" such as roads, bridges, canals, and harbours.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He also encouraged invention and new ideas through his patent enforcement and support of infant industry monopolies.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He supported partial public subsidies for elementary education, and he believed that competition among religious institutions would provide general benefit to the society.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Finally, he outlined how the government should support the dignity of the monarch or chief magistrate, such that they are equal or above the public in fashion.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] He further stated that monarchs should be provided for in a greater fashion than magistrates of a republic because "we naturally expect more splendor in the court of a king than in the mansion-house of a doge".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] However, he added that in general, a retaliatory tariff "seems a bad method of compensating the injury done to certain classes of our people, to do another injury ourselves, not only to those classes, but to almost all the other classes of them".
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Economic historians such as Jacob Viner regard Smith as a strong advocate of free markets and limited government (what Smith called "natural liberty"), but not as a dogmatic supporter of *laissez-faire*.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The economist Daniel Klein believes using the term "free-market economics" or "free-market economist" to identify the ideas of Smith is too general and slightly misleading.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Klein offers six characteristics central to the identity of Smith's economic thought and argues that a new name is needed to give a more accurate depiction of the "Smithian" identity.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] The economist David Ricardo set straight some of the misunderstandings about Smith's thoughts on free market.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Many continue to fall victim to the thinking that Smith was a free-market economist without exception, though he was not.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Ricardo pointed out that Smith was in support of helping infant industries.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith believed that the government should subsidise newly formed industry, but he did fear that when the infant industry grew into adulthood, it would be unwilling to surrender the government help.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith also supported tariffs on imported goods to counteract an internal tax on the same good.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Smith also fell to pressure in supporting some tariffs in support for national defence.
[src:article-of-commerce/adam-smith-p02] Some have also argued, Emma Rothschild among them, that Smith would have supported a minimum wage, although no direct textual evidence supports the claim.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou is the son of the mathematician Raymond Badiou (1905–1996), who was a member of the Resistance in France during World War II.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Alain Badiou was a student at the Lycée Louis-le-Grand and then the École Normale Supérieure (1955–1960).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou was politically active very early on, and was one of the founding members of the Unified Socialist Party (PSU).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The PSU was particularly active in the struggle for the decolonization of Algeria.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He wrote his first novel, *Almagestes*, in 1964.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In 1967 he joined a study group organized by Louis Althusser, became increasingly influenced by Jacques Lacan and became a member of the editorial board of *Cahiers pour l'Analyse*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] By then he "already had a solid grounding in mathematics and logic (along with Lacanian theory)", and his own two contributions to the pages of *Cahiers* "anticipate many of the distinctive concerns of his later philosophy".
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The student uprisings of May 1968 reinforced Badiou's commitment to the far Left, and he participated in increasingly militant groups, such as the Union des communistes de France marxiste-léniniste (UCFml).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] To quote Badiou himself, the UCFml is "the Maoist organization established in late 1969 by Natacha Michel, Sylvain Lazarus, myself and a fair number of young people".
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] During this time, Badiou joined the faculty of the newly founded University of Paris VIII (Vincennes-Saint Denis) which was a bastion of counter-cultural thought.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] There he engaged in fierce intellectual debates with fellow professors Gilles Deleuze and Jean-François Lyotard, whose philosophical works he considered unhealthy deviations from the Althusserian program of a scientific Marxism.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Nonetheless, Badiou has never renounced Althusser or Lacan, and sympathetic references to Marxism and psychoanalysis are not uncommon in his more recent works (most notably *Petit panthéon portatif* / *Pocket Pantheon*).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He took up his current position at the École Normale Supérieure in 1999.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He is also associated with a number of other institutions, such as the Collège International de Philosophie.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He was a member of L'Organisation Politique (OP) which he founded in 1985 with some comrades from the Maoist UCFml – this organization disbanded in 2007.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In 2002, Badiou was a co-founder of the Centre International d'Etude de la Philosophie Française Contemporaine, alongside Yves Duroux and his former student Quentin Meillassoux.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou has also enjoyed success as a dramatist with plays such as *Ahmed le Subtil*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In the last decade, an increasing number of Badiou's works have been translated into English, such as *Ethics*, *Deleuze*, *Manifesto for Philosophy*, *Metapolitics*, and *Being and Event*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Short pieces by Badiou have likewise appeared in American and English periodicals, such as *Lacanian Ink*, *New Left Review*, *Radical Philosophy*, *Cosmos and History* and *Parrhesia*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In 2014–15, Badiou had the role of Honorary President at the Global Center for Advanced Studies.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou makes repeated use of several concepts throughout his philosophy, which he discerns from close readings of the philosophical literature from the classical period.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] His own method cannot be fully understood if it is not situated within the tradition of French academic philosophy.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou's work engages a detailed decrypting of texts, in line with philosophers such as Foucault, Deleuze, Balibar, Bourdieu, Derrida, Bouveresse and Engel, all of whom he studied with at the Ecole Normale Superieure.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] One of the aims of his thought is to show that his categories of truth are useful for any type of philosophical critique.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Therefore, he uses them to interrogate art and history as well as ontology and scientific discovery.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Johannes Thumfart argues that Badiou's philosophy can be regarded as a contemporary reinterpretation of Platonism.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Truth, for Badiou, is a specifically philosophical category.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] While philosophy's several conditions are, on their own terms, "truth procedures" (i.e., they produce truths as they are pursued), it is only philosophy that can speak of the several truth procedures *as* truth procedures.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] (The lover, for instance, does not think of her love as a question of truth, but simply and rightly as a question of love.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Only the philosopher sees in the true lover's love the unfolding of a truth.) Badiou has a very rigorous notion of truth, one that is strongly against the grain of much of contemporary European thought.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou at once embraces the traditional modernist notion that truths are genuinely invariant (always and everywhere the case, eternal and unchanging) and the incisively postmodernist notion that truths are constructed through processes.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The idea, here, is that a truth's invariance makes it genuinely indiscernible: because a truth is everywhere and always the case, it passes unnoticed unless there is a rupture in the laws of being and appearance, during which the truth in question becomes, but only for a passing moment, discernible.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Such a rupture is what Badiou calls an event, according to a theory originally worked out in *Being and Event* and fleshed out in important ways in *Logics of Worlds*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The individual who chances to witness such an event, if he is faithful to what he has glimpsed, can then introduce the truth by naming it into worldly situations.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] For Badiou, it is by positioning oneself to the truth of an event that a human animal becomes a subject; subjectivity is not an inherent human trait.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] While such knowledge is produced in the process of being faithful to a truth event, for Badiou, knowledge, in the figure of the encyclopedia, always remains fragile, subject to what may yet be produced as faithful subjects of the event produce further knowledge.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] According to Badiou, truth procedures proceed to infinity, such that faith (fidelity) outstrips knowledge.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] (Badiou, following both Lacan and Heidegger, distances truth from knowledge.) The dominating ideology of the day, which Badiou terms *democratic materialism*, denies the existence of truth and only recognizes bodies and languages.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou proposes a turn towards the materialist dialectic, which recognizes that there are only bodies and languages, *except* there are also truths.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Art is immanent in the sense that its truth is given in its immediacy in a given work of art, and singular in that its truth is found in art and art alone—hence reviving the ancient materialist concept of "aesthesis".
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] His view of the link between philosophy and art is tied into the motif of pedagogy, which he claims functions so as to "arrange the forms of knowledge in a way that some truth may come to pierce a hole in them".
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He develops these ideas with examples from the prose of Samuel Beckett and the poetry of Stéphane Mallarmé and Fernando Pessoa (who he argues has developed a body of work that philosophy is currently incapable of incorporating), among others.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The major propositions of Badiou's philosophy all find their basis in his book, in which he continues his attempt (which he began in *Théorie du sujet*) to reconcile a notion of the subject with ontology, and in particular post-structuralist and constructivist ontologies.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] A frequent criticism of post-structuralist work is that it prohibits, through its fixation on semiotics and language, any notion of a subject.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou's work is, by his own admission, an attempt to break out of contemporary philosophy's fixation upon language, which he sees almost as a straitjacket.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] This effort leads him, in *Being and Event*, to combine rigorous mathematical formulae with his readings of poets such as Mallarmé and Hölderlin and religious thinkers such as Pascal.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] His philosophy draws upon both 'analytical' and 'continental' traditions.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In Badiou's own opinion, this combination places him awkwardly relative to his contemporaries, meaning that his work had been only slowly taken up.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] *Being and Event* offers an example of this slow uptake, in fact: it was translated into English only in 2005, a full seventeen years after its French publication.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] This situation of being and the rupture which characterizes the event are thought in terms of set theory, and specifically Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In short, the event is a truth caused by a hidden "part" or set appearing within existence; this part escapes language and known existence, and thus being itself lacks the terms and resources to fully process the event.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] For Badiou the problem which the Greek tradition of philosophy has faced and never satisfactorily dealt with is that while beings themselves are plural, and thought in terms of multiplicity, being itself is thought to be singular; that is, *it* is thought in terms of the one.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He proposes as the solution to this impasse the following declaration: that the One is not (*l'Un n'est pas*).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] This is why Badiou accords set theory (the axioms of which he refers to as the "ideas of the multiple") such stature, and refers to mathematics as the very place of ontology: Only set theory allows one to conceive a 'pure doctrine of the multiple'.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Set theory does not operate in terms of definite individual elements in groupings but only functions insofar as what belongs to a set is of the same relation as that set (that is, another set too).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] What individuates a set, therefore, is not an existential positive proposition, but other multiples whose properties (i.e., *structural* relations) validate its presentation.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The *structure* of being thus secures the regime of the count-as-one.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] So if one is to think of a set – for instance, the set of people, or humanity – as counting as one, the multiple elements which belong to that set are secured as one consistent concept (humanity), but only in terms of what does *not* belong to that set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] It may help to understand the concept 'count-as-one' if it is associated with the concept of 'terming': a multiple is *not* one, but it is referred to with 'multiple': one word.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] To count a set as one is to mention that set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] 'Terminology' implies precisely difference between terms (thus multiplicity) as the condition for meaning.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The idea of a term without meaning is incoherent, the count-as-one is a *structural effect* or a *situational operation*; it is not an event of 'truth'.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Multiples which are 'composed' or 'consistent' are count-effects.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou's use of set theory in this manner is not just illustrative or heuristic.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou uses the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory to identify the relationship of being to history, Nature, the State, and God.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Most significantly this use means that (as with set theory) there is a strict prohibition on self-belonging; a set cannot contain or belong to itself.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] This results from the axiom of foundation – or the axiom of regularity – which enacts such a prohibition (cf. p.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] (This axiom states that every non-empty set A contains an element y that is disjoint from A.) Badiou's philosophy draws two major implications from this prohibition.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Firstly, it secures the inexistence of the 'one': there cannot be a grand overarching set, and thus it is fallacious to conceive of a grand cosmos, a whole Nature, or a Being of God.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou is therefore – against Georg Cantor, from whom he draws heavily – staunchly atheist.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] However, secondly, this prohibition prompts him to introduce the event.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Because, according to Badiou, the axiom of foundation 'founds' all sets in the void, it ties all being to the historico-social situation of the multiplicities of de-centred sets – thereby effacing the positivity of subjective action, or an entirely 'new' occurrence.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] And whilst this is acceptable ontologically, it is unacceptable, Badiou holds, philosophically.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Set theory mathematics has consequently 'pragmatically abandoned' an area which philosophy cannot.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] And so, Badiou argues, there is therefore only one possibility remaining: that ontology can say nothing about the event.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Several critics have questioned Badiou's use of mathematics.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Mathematician Alan Sokal and physicist Jean Bricmont write that Badiou proposes, with seemingly "utter seriousness," a blending of psychoanalysis, politics and set theory that they contend is preposterous.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] When these things appear in Badiou's texts it is always allusively, with fragments of symbolism detached from the context that endows them with sense, and often with free variables and bound variables colliding randomly.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] No proof is clearly stated or examined, and the jargon of set theory is waved like a magician's wand, to give authority to bursts of all but unintelligible metaphysics.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] An example of a critique from a mathematician's point of view is the essay 'Badiou's Number: A Critique of Mathematics as Ontology' by Ricardo L.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Nirenberg and David Nirenberg, which takes issue in particular with Badiou's matheme of the Event in *Being and Event*, which has already been alluded to in respect of the 'axiom of foundation' above.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] is here defined in terms of itself; you must already have it in order to define it.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Set theorists call this a not-well-founded set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou again turns here to mathematics and set theory – Badiou's language of ontology – to study the possibility of an indiscernible element existing extrinsically to the situation of ontology.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He employs the strategy of the mathematician Paul J.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Cohen, using what are called the *conditions* of sets.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] These conditions are thought of in terms of domination, a domination being that which defines a set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] (If one takes, in binary language, the set with the condition 'items marked only with ones', any item marked with zero negates the property of the set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The condition which has only ones is thus dominated by any condition which has zeros in it [cf. pp.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] 367–371 in *Being and Event*].) Badiou reasons using these conditions that every discernible (nameable or constructible) set is dominated by the conditions which don't possess the property that makes it discernible as a set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] (The property 'one' is always dominated by 'not one'.) These sets are, in line with constructible ontology, relative to one's being-in-the-world and one's being in language (where sets and concepts, such as the concept 'humanity', get their names).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] One does not necessarily need to refer to constructible language to conceive of a 'set of dominations', which he refers to as the indiscernible set, or the generic set.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] It is, therefore, he continues, possible to think beyond the strictures of the relativistic constructible universe of language, by a process Cohen calls forcing.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou thereby marks out a philosophy by which to refute the apparent relativism or apoliticism in post-structuralist thought.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Badiou's ultimate ethical maxim is therefore one of: "decide upon the undecidable".
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] It is to name the indiscernible, the generic set, and thus name the event that re-casts ontology in a new light.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He identifies four domains in which a subject (who *becomes* a subject through this process) can potentially witness an event: love, science, politics and art.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] By enacting fidelity to the event within these four domains one performs a 'generic procedure', which in its undecidability is necessarily experimental, and one potentially recasts the situation in which being takes place.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Through this maintenance of fidelity, truth has the potentiality to emerge.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In line with his concept of the event, Badiou maintains, politics is not about politicians, but activism based on the present situation and the evental [*sic*] (his translators' neologism) rupture.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] So too does love have this characteristic of becoming *anew*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Even in science the guesswork that marks the event is prominent.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] He vigorously rejects the tag of 'decisionist' (the idea that once something is decided it 'becomes true'), but rather argues that the recasting of a truth comes prior to its veracity or verifiability.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] When Galileo announced the principle of inertia, he was still separated from the truth of the new physics by all the chance encounters that are named in subjects such as Descartes or Newton.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] While Badiou is keen to reject an equivalence between politics and philosophy, he correlates nonetheless his political activism and skepticism toward the parliamentary-democratic process with his philosophy, based around singular, situated truths, and potential revolutions.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Alain Badiou is a founding member (along with Natacha Michel and Sylvain Lazarus) of the militant French political organisation L'Organisation Politique, which was active from 1985 until it disbanded in 2007.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] It called itself a post-party organization concerned with direct popular intervention in a wide range of issues (including immigration, labor, and housing).
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In addition to numerous writings and interventions, L'Organisation Politique highlighted the importance of developing political prescriptions concerning undocumented migrants (*les sans papiers*), stressing that they must be conceived primarily as workers and not immigrants.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] In 2005, a controversy in Parisian intellectual life erupted after the publication of Badiou's *Circonstances 3: Portées du mot 'juif'* ("The Uses of the Word 'Jew'").
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The author criticised Israel's "identitarian claim to be a Jewish state" and advocated for a secular Palestine in its place.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] This book generated a strong response, and the wrangling became a *cause célèbre* with articles going back and forth in the French newspaper *Le Monde* and in the cultural journal *Les Temps modernes*.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Linguist and Lacanian philosopher Jean-Claude Milner, a past president of Collège international de philosophie, accused Badiou of anti-Semitism.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Everyone agrees, it seems, on the point that the Taliban do not embody the path of modernity for Afghanistan.” A modern democracy, he writes, must count all its residents as citizens, and "there is no acceptable reason to exempt the state of Israel from that rule.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] The claim is sometimes made that this state is the only 'democratic' state in the region.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Alain Badiou gained notoriety in 2007 with his pamphlet *The Meaning of Sarkozy* (*De quoi Sarkozy est-il le nom?*), which quickly sold 60,000 copies, whereas for 40 years the sales of his books had oscillated between 2,000 and 6,000 copies.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] As Rafael Behr pointed out at the time (in 2009), Badiou despised Sarkozy and barely could write his name.
[src:article-of-commerce/alain-badiou] Instead, Badiou usually called Sarkozy "the Rat Man" throughout *The Meaning of Sarkozy.* Steven Poole also pointed out that this characterization (Rat Man) brought charges of antisemitism against Badiou.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The daughter of an Imperial Russian Army general, Kollontai embraced radical politics in the 1890s and joined the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party (RSDLP) in 1899.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] During the RSDLP ideological split, she sided with Julius Martov's Mensheviks against Lenin's Bolsheviks.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Exiled from Russia in 1908, Kollontai toured Western Europe and the United States and campaigned against participation in the First World War.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1915, she broke with the Mensheviks and became a member of the Bolsheviks.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Following the 1917 February Revolution which ousted Emperor Nicholas II, Kollontai returned to Russia.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She supported Lenin's radical proposals and, as a member of the party's Central Committee, voted for the policy of armed uprising which led to the October Revolution and the fall of Alexander Kerensky's Provisional Government.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was appointed People's Commissar for Social Welfare in the first Soviet government, but soon resigned due to her opposition to the peace treaty of Brest-Litovsk in the ranks of the Left Communists.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1919, Kollontai was a leading figure in the foundation of the Zhenotdel, the then-new women's department of the Central Committee that was aimed at improving the status of women in the Soviet Union.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was a champion of women's liberation, and later came to be recognized as a key figure in Marxist feminism.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai was outspoken against bureaucratic influences over the Communist Party and its undemocratic internal practices.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] To that end, she sided with the left-wing Workers' Opposition in 1920, but was eventually defeated and sidelined, narrowly avoiding her own expulsion from the party altogether.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] From 1922 on, she was appointed to various diplomatic posts abroad, serving in Norway, Mexico and Sweden.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] This period in her life is captured in the writing of fellow Plenipotentiary from Spain, Isabel de Palencia, titled *Alexandra Kollontay, Ambassadress from Russia*, published in 1947.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1943, she was promoted to the title of ambassador to Sweden.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai retired from diplomatic service in 1945 and died in Moscow in 1952.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai's father, General Mikhail Alekseyevich Domontovich (1830–1902), descended from a Ukrainian family that traced its ancestry back to the 13th century, to Daumantas (Dovmont), prince of Pskov from 1266 to 1299, later canonized as a saint by the Russian Orthodox Church.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Her father served as a cavalry officer in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] After his participation in the war, he was a member of the Russian staff advising the Bulgarian Constituent Assembly.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] He entertained liberal political views, favouring a constitutional monarchy like that of United Kingdom.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In the 1880s, he wrote a study of the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] This study was confiscated by tsarist censors, presumably for showing insufficient Russian nationalist zeal.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra's mother, Alexandra Alexandrovna Masalina (Massalina) (1848–1899), was the daughter of Alexander Feodorovich Masalin (Massalin) (1809–1859), a Finnish peasant who had made a fortune selling wood.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra Alexandrovna Masalina became known as Alexandra Alexandrovna Masalina-Mravinskaya after her marriage to her first husband, Konstantin Iosipovich Mravinsky (originally spelled Mrovinsky) (1829–1921).
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Her marriage to Mravinsky was an arranged marriage which turned out to be unhappy, and eventually she divorced Mravinsky in order to marry Mikhail Domontovich, with whom she had fallen in love.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Russian opera singer Yevgeniya Mravina (stage name) was Kollontai's half-sister via her mother.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The celebrated Soviet-Russian conductor Yevgeny Mravinsky, music director of the Leningrad Philharmonic Orchestra for fifty years (1938–1988), was the only son of Mravina's brother Alexander Kostantinovich and thus Kollontai's half nephew.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra Mikhailovna Domontovich was born on 31 March [O.S.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] "Shura", as she was called growing up, was close to her father, with whom she shared an analytical bent and an interest in history and politics.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Her relationship with her mother, for whom she was named, was more complex.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra was a good student growing up, sharing her father's interest in history, and mastering a range of languages.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She spoke French with her mother and sisters, English with her nanny, Finnish with the peasants at a family estate inherited from her maternal grandfather in Kuusa (in Muolaa, Grand Duchy of Finland), and was a student of German.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra sought to continue her schooling at a university, but her mother refused her permission, arguing that women had no real need for higher education, and that impressionable youngsters encountered too many dangerous radical ideas at universities.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Instead, Alexandra was to be allowed to take an exam to gain certification as a school teacher before making her way into society to find a husband, as was the custom.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1890 or 1891, Alexandra, aged around 19, met her cousin and future husband, Vladimir Ludvigovich Kollontai (9 July 1867 – July/August 1917), an engineering student of modest means enrolled at a military institute.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra's mother objected bitterly to the potential union since the young man was so poor, to which her daughter replied that she would work as a teacher to help make ends meet.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Her parents forbade the relationship and sent Alexandra on a tour of Western Europe in the hope that she would forget Vladimir, but the pair remained committed to one another despite it all and married in 1893.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra became pregnant soon after her marriage and bore a son, Mikhail, in 1894.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She devoted her time to reading radical populist and Marxist political literature and writing fiction.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] While Kollontai was initially drawn to the populist ideas of restructuring society based upon the Mir commune, she soon abandoned this for other revolutionary projects.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Marxism, with its emphasis on the class consciousness of factory workers, the revolutionary seizure of power, and the construction of modern industrial society, attracted Kollontai and many of her peers in Russia's radical intelligentsia.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai's first activities were timid and modest, helping out a few hours a week with her sister Zhenia at a library that supported Sunday classes in basic literacy for urban workers, sneaking a few socialist ideas into the lessons.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Through this library Kollontai met Elena Stasova, an activist in the budding Marxist movement in St.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Stasova began to use Kollontai as a courier, transporting parcels of illegal writings to unknown individuals, which were delivered upon utterance of a password.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Years later, she wrote about her marriage, "We separated although we were in love because I felt trapped.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] I was detached, [from Vladimir], because of the revolutionary upsettings rooted in Russia." In 1898 she left little Mikhail with her parents to study economics in Zürich, Switzerland, with Professor Heinrich Herkner.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She then paid a visit to England, where she met members of the British socialist movement, including Sidney and Beatrice Webb.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She returned to Russia in 1899, at which time she met Vladimir Ilych Ulyanov, better known today as Vladimir Lenin.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai became interested in Marxist ideas while studying the history of working movements in Zürich, under Herkner, later described by her as a Marxist Revisionist.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She became a member of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party in 1899 at the age of 27.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1905, Kollontai was a witness to the series of events in Saint Petersburg, known as Bloody Sunday, where tsarist soldiers opened fire on unarmed demonstrators in front of the Winter Palace causing hundreds of deaths and injuries.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] At the time of the split in the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party between the Mensheviks under Julius Martov and the Bolsheviks under Vladimir Lenin in 1903, Kollontai did not side with either faction at first, and "offered her services to both factions".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1906, however, disapproving of "the hostile position taken by the Bolsheviks towards the Duma" and despite her being generally a left-winger, she decided to join the Mensheviks.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She went into exile, to Germany, in 1908 after publishing "Finland and Socialism", which called on the Finnish people to rise up against oppression within the Russian Empire.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She traveled across western Europe and became acquainted with Karl Kautsky, Clara Zetkin, Rosa Luxemburg, and Karl Liebknecht, among others.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1911, while abruptly breaking off her long-term relationship with her faction comrade Peter Maslov (1867–1946), an agrarian scientist, she started a love affair with another fellow exilee, Alexander Gavrilovich Shliapnikov.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The couple appeared quite oddly assorted: she was a Menshevik intellectual, of noble origins, thirteen years older than him; he was a self-taught metalworker from provincial Russia and a Bolshevik leading exponent of some prominence.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Their romantic relationship came to an end in July 1916, but evolved thereafter into a long-lasting friendship as they wound up sharing many of the same general political views.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] They were still in contact in the early 1930s when Kollontai lived abroad in a sort of diplomatic exile, and Shliapnikov was going to be executed during the Soviet purges.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] With Russian entry into World War I in 1914, Kollontai left Germany due to the German social democrats' support of the war.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai was strongly opposed to the war and very outspoken against it, and in June 1915 she broke with the Mensheviks and officially joined the Bolsheviks, "those who most consistently fought social-patriotism".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] After leaving Germany, Kollontai traveled to Denmark, only to discover that the Danish social democrats also supported the war.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The next place where Kollontai tried to speak and write against the war was Sweden, but the Swedish government imprisoned her for her activities.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] After her release, Kollontai traveled to Norway, where she at last found a socialist community that was receptive to her ideas.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai stayed primarily in Norway until 1917.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She travelled twice to the United States to speak about war and politics, and to renew her relationship with her son Mikhail; in 1916, she had arranged for him to avoid conscription by going to the United States to work on Russian orders from U.S. factories.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1917, upon hearing of the February Revolution, Kollontai returned from Norway to Russia.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] When Lenin returned to Russia in April 1917, Kollontai was the only major leader of the Petrograd Bolsheviks who immediately voiced her full support for his April theses, a set of radical and nonconformist proposals.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was a member of the Executive Committee of the Petrograd Soviet, and "for the rest of 1917, [she] was a constant agitator for revolution in Russia as a speaker, leaflet writer and worker on the Bolshevik women's paper *Rabotnitsa*".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] At the Second All-Russian Congress of Soviets on 26 October, she was elected People's Commissar for Social Welfare in the first Soviet government, but she soon resigned in opposition to the Brest-Litovsk Peace.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] During the revolutionary period, at the age of 45, she married 28-year-old revolutionary sailor Pavel Dybenko, while keeping her surname from her first marriage.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was the most prominent woman in the Soviet administration and was best known for founding the Zhenotdel or "Women's Department" in 1919 .
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] This organization worked to improve the conditions of women's lives in the Soviet Union, fighting illiteracy and educating women about the new marriage, education, and work laws put in place by the Revolution.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] "Kollontai's propositions for reform mostly repeated those enumerated by the Workers' Opposition, but she placed a greater emphasis on reducing 'bureaucratisation'," and denouncing petty-bourgeois or non-proletarian influences on Soviet institutions and on the party.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Her language "conveyed much harsher criticism of the party and CC than did Shlyapnikov's language" in the official faction platform.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Lenin was very upset about Kollontai joining the Workers' Opposition and, when he was given a copy of her pamphlet, he just 'leafed through' it and immediately castigated Kollontai.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The followers of the faction among the delegates, however, remained quite few and proved to be declining during the proceedings, when Lenin did not even hesitate to draw snickers from delegates by hinting at the amatory past of the Kollontai-Shliapnikov couple.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Thus, the Workers' Opposition was forcibly dissolved, and Kollontai was practically sidelined.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In her speech, she bitterly attacked the New Economic Policy proposed by Lenin, warning that it 'threatened to disillusion workers, to strengthen the peasantry and petty bourgeoisie, and to facilitate the rebirth of capitalism'.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] When 'Kollontai attempted to speak before the Comintern Executive on 26 February 1922 on behalf of the views expressed in the appeal,' Trotsky and Zinoviev had her name removed from the list of orators and insisted that she should not take the floor.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] When she 'proved recalcitrant, Trotsky forbade her to speak and issued a decree, in the name of the CC, ordering all members of the Russian delegation to "obey the directives of the party".' Predictably, the appeal of the 22 was unsuccessful.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] At the Eleventh Party Congress (March–April 1922), Kollontai, Shlyapnikov and Medvedev were charged with having insisted on factional work and a three-man commission, Stalin, Zinoviev and Dzerzhinsky, recommended the "unrepentant" three be purged from the party.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] But even outside the ranks of our party, I will live, work and fight for the Communist party." Eventually, a resolution was passed allowing the three to remain in the party unless they committed further violations of its discipline.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] After the Eleventh Congress, Kollontai became a political outcast.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was badly shaken by having teetered dangerously close to expulsion, and regarded the idea of being excluded from the 'revolutionary community of the elect' as a dreadful "nightmare".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She even speculated she might be arrested.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] During this time, Kollontai was also in the process of a painful divorce from her second husband, Pavel Dybenko, which made her want a change of scenery.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In the latter half of 1922 she wrote a "personal letter" to the newly appointed General Secretary of the Central Committee and her recent inquisitor, Joseph Stalin, asking to be sent on a mission abroad.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Stalin granted her request and, starting from October 1922, she began to be entrusted with diplomatic appointments abroad and was thus prevented from playing any further political role at home.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] At first she hoped it was just a passing phase in her life and that she would soon return to her political work in the Zhenotdel, but eventually she had to realize that the diplomatic assignment had become a sort of exile.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Initially, she was sent as an attaché to the Soviet commercial mission in Norway, becoming one of the first women serving in diplomacy in modern times.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In early 1924, Kollontai was first promoted to *Chargé d'affaires* and from August to Minister Plenipotentiary.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] As such, she later served in Mexico (1926–27), again in Norway (1927–30) and eventually in Sweden (1930–45), where she was finally promoted to Ambassador in 1943.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was also a member of the Soviet delegation to the League of Nations.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] When Kollontai was in Stockholm, the Winter War between Russia and Finland broke out; it has been said that it was largely due to her influence that Sweden remained neutral.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] After the war, she received Vyacheslav Molotov's praises.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] During late April 1943, Kollontai may have been involved in abortive peace negotiations with Hans Thomsen, her German counterpart in Stockholm.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai was cared for by her friend, Swedish doctor Ada Nilsson as her health began to fail and retired in 1945.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Being sent abroad in a sort of *de facto* exile for over twenty years, Kollontai gave up "her fight for reform and for women, retreating into relative obscurity" and bowing to the new political climate.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She discarded her feminist concerns and "offered no objection to the patriarchal legislation of 1926 and the constitution of 1936, which deprived Soviet women of many of the gains they had achieved after the February and October Revolutions".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The following words she allegedly pronounced in a private conversation with her friend Marcel Body in 1929 give a suggestion of her attitude towards advancing Stalinism: "Everything's changed so much.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] On asking the publisher to make the changes requested, Kollontai apologized with obvious embarrassment, inviting repeatedly to debit her all expenses and writing twice that, under current circumstances, it was not absolutely possible "to do otherwise".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In his memoirs, Leon Trotsky was contemptuously critical of Kollontai's political attitude, writing that 'In Russia, Kolontay took from the very first an ultra-left stand, not only toward me but toward Lenin as well.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] — *Oppozitsiia i partiinaia massa* [The Opposition and the Party Rank and File], "*Pravda*", 30 October 1927, p.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The degree of her adherence to the prevailing ideas of the Stalinist regime, whether it was spontaneous or not, may be gauged from the opening of an article she wrote in 1946 for a Russian magazine.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] It bore the title *The Soviet Woman — a Full and Equal Citizen of Her Country*, and praised the Soviet Union's advances of women's rights, while simultaneously emphasizing a view of the role of women in society at odds with her previous writings on women's liberation.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] — *Sovetskaya zhenshchina* [Soviet Woman], 5, September–October 1946, pp.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Alexandra Kollontai died in Moscow on 9 March 1952, less than a month from her 80th birthday, and was buried at Novodevichy Cemetery.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She was the only member of the Bolsheviks' Central Committee that had led the October Revolution who managed to live into the 1950s, other than Stalin and his devoted supporter Matvei Muranov.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She has sometimes been criticized and even held up to contempt for not raising her voice during the Stalinist purges, when, among countless others, her former husband, her former lover and fighting comrade, and so many friends of hers were executed.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] And, it has been noted, at the time she "was safe in her sumptuous Stockholm residence".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Notwithstanding, it should also be pointed out that, even so, Kollontai did not enjoy a full liberty of action and had to worry about the possible fates of her family.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] It might not have been pure chance if both her only son and her musician half-nephew (whom she had much supported at the beginning of his career) also came unscathed through the persecution of the Stalinist regime, to the establishment of which she had, however, significantly contributed.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The resurgence of radicalism in the 1960s and the growth of the feminist movement in the 1970s spurred a new interest in the life and writings of Alexandra Kollontai all around the world.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] A spate of books and pamphlets by and about Kollontai were subsequently published, including full-length biographies by historians Cathy Porter, Beatrice Farnsworth, and Barbara Evans Clements.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In 1982 Rosa von Praunheim made the film *Red Love* based on the novella with the same title by Kollontai; the film was shown in the Museum of Modern Art.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai was the subject of the 1994 TV film, *A Wave of Passion: The Life of Alexandra Kollontai,* with Glenda Jackson as the voice of Kollontai.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] A female Soviet diplomat in the 1930s with unconventional views on sexuality, probably inspired by Kollontai, had been played by Greta Garbo in the movie *Ninotchka* (1939).
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai is regarded as a key figure in Marxist feminism for her commitment both to women's liberation and Marxist ideals.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She opposed the ideology of liberal feminism, which she saw as bourgeois.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] At the same time, Kollontai was a champion of women's liberation, believing that it "could take place only as the result of the victory of a new social order and a different economic system".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai is known for her advocacy of free love.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] However, this does not mean that she advocated casual sexual encounters; indeed, she believed that due to the inequality between men and women that persisted under socialism, such encounters would lead to women being exploited, and being left to raise children alone.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Instead she believed that true socialism could not be achieved without a radical change in attitudes to sexuality, so that it might be freed from the oppressive norms that she saw as a continuation of bourgeois ideas about property.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] A common myth describes her as a proponent of the "glass of water" theory of sexuality.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] The quote "...the satisfaction of one's sexual desires should be as simple as getting a glass of water" is often mistakenly attributed to her.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Though Kollontai believed in the eventual obsolescence of the traditional family, she held that the institution of marriage could survive if it underwent a radical transformation.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She advocated for a transformed marriage that would be compatible with many other social relations, such as friendship.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai felt that by liberating women and men from their traditionally hierarchical roles, communism would free marriage from the "conjugal slavery of the past", allowing spouses to thrive in egalitarian marriages grounded in mutual love and trust.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai saw domestic labour as an impediment to her ideal of the "universal family".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] In this regard, Kollontai's critique of women's societal position under capitalism is both reminiscent of and distinct from the Marxist feminist Wages for Housework movement.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] While proponents of Wages for Housework argue that the domestic labour is productive labour worthy of monetary compensation, Kollontai devalued "women's work", believing it to be an antiquated vestige of the past.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai's views on the role of marriage and the family under Communism were arguably more influential than her advocacy of "free love".
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Kollontai believed that, like the state, the family unit would wither away once the second stage of communism became a reality.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] She viewed marriage and traditional families as legacies of an oppressive, property-rights-based, and individualistic past in which women were simultaneously subjected to both wage labour outside the home and unpaid maternal and domestic labour within it.
[src:article-of-commerce/alexandra-kollontai] Similarly, their children would be wards of society, raised in common.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga was born at Resina in the province of Naples in 1889.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] His father, Oreste Bordiga, was an esteemed scholar of agricultural science, whose authority was especially recognized regarding the centuries-old agricultural problems of Southern Italy.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] His mother, Zaira degli Amadei, was descended from an ancient Florentine family, and his maternal grandfather Count Michele Amadei was a conspirator in the struggles of the Risorgimento.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] His paternal uncle, Giovanni Bordiga, another militant of the *Risorgimento*, was a mathematician and professor at the University of Padua.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] An opponent of the Italo-Turkish War as an Italian colonial war in Libya, Bordiga was introduced to the Italian Socialist Party (PSI) by his high-school physics teacher in 1910.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga eventually founded the Karl Marx Circle in 1912, where he would meet his first wife, Ortensia De Meo.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga graduated with a degree in engineering from the University of Naples in 1912.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Ortensia died in 1955, and Bordiga married Ortensia's sister, Antonietta De Meo, ten years later in 1965.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Within the newly founded "Karl Marx Circle", Bordiga rejected a pedagogical approach to political work and developed a "theory of the Party", whereby the organization was meant to display non-immediate goals as a rally of similarly minded people and not necessarily a body of the working class.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga was deeply opposed to representative democracy, which he associated with bourgeois electoralism.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In a 1914 issue of *Il Socialista*, he wrote: "Thus, if there is a complete negation of the theory of democratic action it is to be found in socialism." Bordiga opposed the parliamentary faction of the PSI being autonomous from central control.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In common with most socialists in Latin countries, Bordiga campaigned against Freemasonry, which he identified as a non-secular group.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Following the October Revolution, Bordiga rallied to the communist movement and formed the communist abstentionist faction within the PSI, abstentionist in that it opposed participation in bourgeois elections.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] The group would form with the addition of the former *L'Ordine Nuovo* grouping in Turin around Antonio Gramsci, the backbone of the Communist Party of Italy (PCdI).
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This came after a long internal struggle in the PSI as it had voted as early as 1919 to affiliate with the Comintern but had refused to purge its reformist wing.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In the course of the conflict, Bordiga attended the 2nd Comintern Congress in 1920, where he added two points to the Twenty-one Conditions of membership proposed by Vladimir Lenin.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] He was, nevertheless, criticized by Lenin in his 1920 work *"Left-Wing" Communism: An Infantile Disorder* over a disagreement regarding parliamentary abstentionism.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] When the PSI held its congress at Livorno in January 1921, representatives sent by the Comintern all insisted that the party must expel its reformist wing led by Filippo Turati, but were divided over whether to continue to work with Giacinto Menotti Serrati, who advised delaying the split.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga advocated an immediate break with both Serrati and Turati, and hence with the majority of the PSI, and prevailed against the opposition of the leading Comintern representative Paul Levi but also with the backing of others, including Matyas Rakosi, the future Stalinist dictator of Hungary.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] After the congress, Bordiga emerged as the leader of the newly formed Communist Party of Italy.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] He was one of five members of the executive but was "the actual director of all party activity".
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This position was accepted by the majority of the members of the PCdI but was to bring them into conflict with the Comintern when in 1921 the latter adopted a new tactic, i.e. that of the united front with reformist organisations to fight for social reforms and even to form a workers' government.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga regarded this as a reversion to the failed tactics which the pre-war social democrats had adopted and which had led to them becoming reformists.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Out of a regard for discipline, Bordiga and his comrades (who became known as the Italian communist left) accepted the Comintern decision but were in an increasingly difficult position.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] When Bordiga was arrested in February 1923 on a trumped-up charge by the new government of Benito Mussolini, he had to give up his post as a member of the Central Committee of the PCdI.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] On his acquittal later that year, Bordiga decided not to reclaim it, therefore implicitly accepting that he was now an oppositionist.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] At the Fifth Congress of Comintern in Moscow held in June–July 1924, Bordiga was the sole voice who opposed any cooperation with socialist parties in favour of a "united front from below, not from above", which received support except within the Italian delegation.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] He argued that the rise of Mussolini and the Italian fascists was only "a change in the governing personnel of the bourgeois class." Also in 1924, the Italian communist left lost control of the PCdI to a pro-Moscow group whose leader Gramsci became the party's General Secretary in June.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In March 1925, Bordiga refused to go to Moscow to attend a plenum of Comintern's executive, and in his absence was accused of taking up a "hostile position against Comintern by declaring his complete solidarity with Trotsky".
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In December 1926, Bordiga was again arrested by Mussolini and sent to prison in Ustica, an Italian island in the Tyrrhenian Sea, where he met with Gramsci, and they renewed their friendship and worked alongside each other despite their political differences.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga was concerned about Gramsci's ill health but nothing came of a plan to help him escape the island.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In 1928, Bordiga was moved to the Isle of Ponza, where he built several houses, returning after his detention in 1929 to finish them.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Following his release, Bordiga did not resume his activities in the PCdI and was in fact expelled in March 1930, accused of having "supported, defended and endorsed the positions of the Trotskyist opposition" and been organisationally disruptive.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] With his expulsion, Bordiga left political activity until 1943, and he was to refuse to comment on political affairs even when asked by trusted friends; many of his former supporters in the PCdI went into exile and founded a political tendency often referred to as Italian communist left.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In 1928, its members in exile in France and Belgium formed themselves into the Left Fraction of the Communist Party of Italy, which became, in 1935, the Italian Fraction of the Communist Left.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This change of name was a reflection of the Italian communist left's view that the PCdI and the other Communist parties had now become counter-revolutionary.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] A faction of the party, with their theory of the party and their opposition to any form of frontism, held that the program was everything and a gate-receipt notion of numbers was nothing.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga would again work with many of these comrades following the end of World War II.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] According to the reports of Angelo Alliotta, a secret informant of the fascist police in Italy who visited Bordiga's home in Formia, where he holidayed with his wife, Bordiga showed support for the Axis powers.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] According to Alliotta, Bordiga believed Nazi Germany was weakening the "English giant", which to him was "the greatest exponent of capitalism", and thus the defeat of Britain would bring about revolutionary conditions in Europe.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga also criticised Joseph Stalin for allying with the Western Allies against the Axis in April 1943.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Other sources cast doubt on the analysis that Bordiga supported Nazi Germany or Fascist Italy, citing ‘contradictory’ testimony on the issue.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] He supported the ‘proletarian’ partisan movements, as well as the anti-fascist Warsaw uprisings of 1943 (Warsaw ghetto) and 1944.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] After 1944, Bordiga first returned to political activity in the Naples-based Fraction of Socialists and Communists.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] When the current split in two in 1951, he took the side of the grouping that took on the name International Communist Party, publishing its *Il Programma Comunista*.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga devoted himself to the party, contributing extensively.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga remained with the ICP until his death at Formia in 1970.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] On the theoretical level, Bordiga developed an understanding of the Soviet Union as what he perceived as a capitalist society.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga's writings on the perceived capitalist nature of the Soviet economy in contrast to those produced by the Trotskyists also focused on the agrarian sector.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In analyzing the agriculture in the Soviet Union, Bordiga sought to display the perceived capitalist social relations that he believed existed in the kolkhoz and sovkhoz, one a cooperative farm and the other a wage-labour state farm.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In particular, he emphasized how much of the national agrarian produce came from small privately owned plots (writing in 1950) and predicted the rates at which the Soviet Union would start importing wheat after Imperial Russia had been such a large exporter from the 1880s to 1914.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In Bordiga's conception of Marxism–Leninism, Joseph Stalin, and later Mao Zedong, Ho Chi Minh, and so on, were great Romantic revolutionaries, i.e. bourgeois revolutionaries.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga defined himself as anti-democracy, believing himself to be following the tradition of Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga's hostility toward democracy was unrelated to the Stalinist narrative of the single-party state, as he saw fascism and Stalinism as the culmination of bourgeois democracy.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Jacques Camatte and Ottorino Perrone) often state that there is no functional difference between democracy and dictatorship, as one class will inevitably establish control.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] To Bordiga, bourgeois democracy meant above all the manipulation of society as a formless mass.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] To this, he counterposed the dictatorship of the proletariat.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] As such, Bordiga opposed the idea of revolutionary theory being the product of a democratic process of pluralist views, believing that the Marxist perspective has the merit of underscoring the fact that, like all social formations, communism is above all about the expression of programmatic content.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This enforces the fact that, for Marxists, communism is not an ideal to be achieved but a real movement born from the old society with a set of programmatic tasks.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga resolutely opposed the Comintern's turn to the right in 1921.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] As leader of the Communist Party of Italy, he refused to implement the united front strategy of the Third Congress.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] He also refused to fuse the newly formed party with the left wing of the Italian Socialist Party from which it had just broken away.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] For Bordiga, the Western European Communist parties' strategy of fighting this ebb by absorbing a mass of left-wing social democrats through the united front was a complete capitulation to the period of counter-revolutionary ebb he saw setting in.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This was the base of his critique of democracy, for it was in the name of conquering the masses that the Comintern seemed to be making all kinds of programmatic concessions to left-wing social democrats.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] For Bordiga, the program was everything; a gate-receipt notion of numbers was nothing.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] The role of the party in the period of ebb was to preserve the program and to carry on the propaganda work possible until the next turn of the tide, not to dilute it while chasing ephemeral popularity.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga's analysis provided a way of seeing a fundamental degeneration in the world communist movement in 1921 (instead of in 1927 with the defeat of Trotsky) without simply calling for more democracy.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] The abstract formal perspective of bureaucracy/democracy, with which the Trotskyist tradition treats this crucial period in Comintern history, became separated from any content.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga, like Lenin, did not see socialism as a separate mode of production from communism but rather how communism looks as it emerges from capitalism before it has "developed on its own foundations".
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga used *socialism* to mean what Marx called the lower-phase communism.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Arguing against what Bordiga saw as the bourgeois idea of "free producer economies", he instead declared that under communism, whether it be the lower stage or higher stage, production and consumption are both enslaved to society.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This view distinguished Bordiga from other Leninists and especially the Trotskyists, who tended and still tend to telescope the first two stages and so have money and the other exchange categories surviving into socialism; Bordiga would have none of this.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] For him, no society in which money, buying, and selling and the rest survived could be regarded as either socialist or communist—these exchange categories would die out before the socialist rather than the communist stage was reached.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Within the Marxist movement, *socialism* was popularised during the Russian Revolution by Lenin.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] This view is consistent with and helped to inform early concepts of socialism in which the law of value no longer directs economic activity.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Monetary relations in the form of exchange-value, profit, interest, and wage labour would not operate and apply to Marxist socialism.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Jacques Camatte began corresponding with Bordiga at the age of 19 in 1954, and Bordiga developed a long-standing relationship with Camatte and ideological influence over him.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Camatte's early work very much reads in line with the Bordigist current, and Bordiga frequently contributed to Camatte's journal *Invariance* near the end of his life.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Even after Camatte's break with Marxism following Bordiga's death, Camatte's preoccupation with the subject of *Gemeinwesen* (community, commonwealth) within Marx's work was consistent with Bordiga's emphasis on the anti-individualist and collectivist aspects of Marxism.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] Bordiga also influenced Gilles Dauvé, and had great influence over the ultra-leftist currents of the 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] The Amadeo Bordiga Foundation was established in 1998 in Formia, in the house where Bordiga spent the last several months of his life.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] The foundation organizes publications of Bordiga's works and encourages further expansions upon his ideas.
[src:article-of-commerce/amadeo-bordiga] In August 2020, *Historical Materialism* published *The Science and Passion of Communism*, an anthology of English translations of Bordiga's work.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In classical political economy and especially Karl Marx's critique of political economy, a **commodity** is any good or service ("products" or "activities") produced by human labour and offered as a product for general sale on the market.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Some other priced goods are also treated as commodities, e.g. human labor-power, works of art and natural resources, even though they may not be produced specifically for the market, or be non-reproducible goods.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] This problem was extensively debated by Adam Smith, David Ricardo, and Karl Rodbertus-Jagetzow, among others.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Value and price are not equivalent terms in Marxist economics, and theorising the specific relationship of value to market price has been a challenge for Marxist economists.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In Marx's theory, a commodity is something that is bought and sold, or exchanged in a relationship of trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Price is then the *monetary expression* of exchange-value, but exchange value could also be expressed as a direct trading ratio between two commodities without using money, and goods could be priced using different valuations or criteria.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] According to the labor theory of value, product-values in an open market are regulated by the average socially necessary labour time required to produce them, and price relativities of products are ultimately governed by the law of value.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Commodity-trade, Marx argues, historically begins at the boundaries of separate economic communities based otherwise on a *non-commercial* form of production.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Thus, producers trade in those goods of which those producers, have episodic or permanent surpluses to their own requirements, and they aim to obtain different goods with an equal value in return.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Marx refers to this as "simple exchange" which implies what Frederick Engels calls "simple commodity production".
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] At first, goods may not even be intentionally produced for the explicit purpose of exchanging them, but as a regular market for goods develops and a cash economy grows, this becomes more and more the case, and production increasingly becomes integrated in commodity trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Even so, in simple commodity production, not all inputs and outputs of the production process are necessarily commodities or priced goods, and it is compatible with a variety of different relations of production ranging from self-employment and family labour to serfdom and slavery.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Typically, however, it is the producer himself who trades his surpluses.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] However, as the division of labour becomes more complex, a class of merchants emerges which specialises in trading commodities, buying here and selling there, without producing products themselves, and parallel to this, property owners emerge who extend credit and charge rents.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] This process goes together with the increased use of money, and the aim of merchants, bankers and renters becomes to gain *income* from the trade, by acting as intermediaries between producers and consumers.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The transformation of a labor-product into a commodity (its "marketing") is in reality not a simple process, but has many technical and social preconditions.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The existence of a social need for it (a market demand) that must be met through trade, or at any event cannot be met otherwise.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The legally sanctioned assertion of private ownership rights to the commodity.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The enforcement of these rights, so that ownership is secure.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The transferability of these private rights from one owner to another.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The (physical) transferability or transmission of the commodity itself, i.e. the ability to store, package, preserve, send and transport it from one owner to another.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The imposition of exclusivity of access to the commodity.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The possibility of the owner to use or consume the commodity privately.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Guarantees about the quality and safety of the commodity, and possibly a guarantee of replacement or service, should it fail to function as intended (see also Complaint tablet to Ea-nāṣir).
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Thus, the "commodification" of a good or service often involves a considerable practical accomplishment in trade.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] It is a process that may be influenced not just by economic or technical factors, but also political and cultural factors, insofar as it involves property rights, claims to access to resources, and guarantees about quality or safety of use.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In absolute terms, exchange values can also be measured as quantities of average labour-hours.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Commodities which contain the same amount of socially necessary labor have the same exchange value.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] By contrast, prices are normally measured in money-units.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] For practical purposes, prices are, however, usually preferable to labour-hours, as units of account, although in capitalist work processes the two are related to each other (see labor power).
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The hyphens ("-") here refer to a transaction applying to an exchange involving goods or money; the dots in the last-mentioned circuit ("...") indicate that a value-forming process ("P") occurs *in between* purchase of commodities and the sales of different commodities.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Thus, while at first merchants are intermediaries between producers and consumers, later capitalist *production* becomes an intermediary between buyers and sellers of commodities.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In that case, the valuation of labour is determined by the value of its products.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] It is possible to extend the Marxian circuit schema's to portray the more complex sequences of phases in international trade and finance.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] This type of representation was pioneered by the French Marxian economist Christian Palloix in his study of multinational firms in the early 1970s.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] The reifying effects of universalised trade in commodities, involving a process Marx calls "commodity fetishism", mean that social relations become expressed as relations between things; for example, price relations.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Markets mediate a complex network of interdependencies and supply chains emerging among people who may not even know who produced the goods they buy, or where they were produced.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] How quantities of use-values are allocated in a market economy depends mainly on their exchange value, and this allocation is mediated by the "cash nexus".
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In Marx's analysis of the capitalist mode of production, commodity sales increase the amount of exchange-value in the possession of the owners of capital, i.e., they yield profit and thus augment their capital (capital accumulation).
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] These components reflect respectively labour costs, the cost of materials and operating expenses including depreciation, and generic profit.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] In capitalism, Marx argues, commodity values are commercially expressed as the prices of production of commodities (cost-price + average profit).
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Prices of production are established jointly by average input costs *and* by the ruling profit margins applying to outputs sold.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] They reflect the fact that production has become totally integrated into the circuits of commodity trade, in which capital accumulation becomes the dominant motive.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] But what prices of production simultaneously hide is the social nature of the valorisation process, i.e. how an increase in capital-value occurs through production.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Likewise, in considering the gross output of capitalist production in an economy as a whole, Marx divides its value into these four components.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] He argues that the total new value added in production, which he calls the value product, consists of the equivalent of variable capital, plus surplus value.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Thus, the workers produce by their labor both a new value equal to their own wages, plus an additional new value which is claimed by capitalists by virtue of their ownership and supply of productive capital.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] By producing new capital in the form of new commodities, Marx argues the working class continuously reproduces the capitalist relations of production; by their work, workers create a new value distributed as both labour-income and property-income.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] If, as free workers, they choose to stop working, the system begins to break down; hence, capitalist civilisation strongly emphasizes the work ethic, regardless of religious belief.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] People must work, because work is the source of new value, profits and capital.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] Marx acknowledged explicitly that not all commodities are products of human labour; all kinds of things can be traded "as if" they are commodities, so long as property rights can be attached to them.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] These are "fictitious commodities" or "pseudo-commodities" or "fiduciary commodities", i.e. their existence as commodities is only nominal or conventional.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] They may not even be tangible objects, but exist only ideally.
[src:article-of-commerce/article-of-commerce] A property right or financial claim, for instance, may be traded as a commodity.
